---
/**
 * UNDERWORLD — the long-form anchor of the page (spec §4.4). Generous
 * layout: multiple prose blocks, pull-quotes, and clearly marked TODO(owner)
 * blocks where the personal essay lands. Themes, in order:
 *   1. Orpheus and Eurydice — the personal anchor
 *   2. Virgil as guide
 *   3. The Furies
 *   4. Soul-marks read after death — sins against kin and nature; greed
 *      stains deepest
 *   5. The Egyptian weighing of the heart against Ma'at's feather
 * Scaffolding prose and classical quotation are provided; the essay itself
 * is TODO(owner).
 */
import Section from '../Section.astro';
import type { SectionSpec } from '../../design/tokens';

interface Props {
  spec: SectionSpec;
}

const { spec } = Astro.props;
---

<Section spec={spec}>
  <h2>Underworld</h2>

  <!-- ── 1. Orpheus and Eurydice — the personal anchor ─────────────── -->
  <article class="block">
    <h3><span data-egg-anchor="underworld-lyre">Orpheus</span>, Looking Back</h3>
    <p class="scaffold">
      The oldest song about song is a song about loss. Orpheus walks down
      singing, wins her back with music alone, and loses her again at the
      edge of the light — because he turns, because love turns.
    </p>
    <blockquote class="pull-quote">
      <p class="greek" lang="la">
        Eurydicen vox ipsa et frigida lingua,<br />
        a miseram Eurydicen! anima fugiente vocabat:<br />
        Eurydicen toto referebant flumine ripae.
      </p>
      <p class="translation">
        "Eurydice" — the voice itself, the tongue already cold, called with
        fleeing breath: "ah, poor Eurydice!" — and "Eurydice" the banks gave
        back along the whole stream.
      </p>
      <cite>Virgil, Georgics IV.525–527</cite>
    </blockquote>
    <div class="todo-block">
      TODO(owner): the personal Orpheus/Eurydice essay — this is the anchor
      of the whole section. What was carried down, what was almost carried
      back, where the look back happened.
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- ── 2. Virgil as guide ────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <article class="block">
    <h3>The Guide</h3>
    <p class="scaffold">
      Every descent needs a guide who has mapped the dark and kept his
      composure in it. Virgil walks ahead through his own poems first —
      the bees of the Georgics fail, and the beekeeper is sent down after
      the reason.
    </p>
    <div class="todo-block">
      TODO(owner): what Virgil (the poet, the guide-figure) means here
      personally — the essay text.
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- ── 3. The Furies ─────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <article class="block">
    <h3>The Kindly Ones</h3>
    <p class="scaffold">
      The Erinyes rise for blood-guilt inside the family: they answer wrongs
      done to kin, and they are older than the Olympian order that tries to
      civilize them. Athens renamed them Eumenides and gave them a home under
      the hill — the debt itself remains payable.
    </p>
    <div class="todo-block">
      TODO(owner): the Furies passage — what pursues, and what settlement
      looks like.
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- ── 4. Soul-marks — sins against kin and nature ───────────────── -->
  <article class="block">
    <h3>Marks on the Soul</h3>
    <p class="scaffold">
      The judges of the dead read the soul the way a physician reads a body:
      every act leaves its scar, and the scars are legible after death. Sins
      against kin and against nature cut deepest, and greed stains deepest of
      all — it dyes the whole fabric through.
    </p>
    <blockquote class="pull-quote">
      <p class="greek" lang="la">quisque suos patimur Manis.</p>
      <p class="translation">Each of us suffers his own shade.</p>
      <cite>Virgil, Aeneid VI.743</cite>
    </blockquote>
    <div class="todo-block">
      TODO(owner): the soul-marks essay — the reckoning of what stains and
      how deep.
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- ── 5. The weighing of the heart ──────────────────────────────── -->
  <article class="block">
    <h3 data-egg-anchor="underworld-feather">The Feather</h3>
    <p class="scaffold">
      In the Egyptian hall of the Two Truths the heart is set on one pan of
      the balance and the feather of Ma'at on the other. The heart that
      weighs the same as truth passes; the heavy heart is given to the
      devourer. The scale is exact, and the feather is the whole standard.
    </p>
    <div class="todo-block">
      TODO(owner): the weighing-of-the-heart close — how the section resolves
      and hands off to Monsoon.
    </div>
  </article>
</Section>

<style>
  h3 {
    font-size: clamp(1.1rem, 2.4vw, 1.5rem);
    font-weight: 400;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--ink);
    margin-bottom: 0.9rem;
  }

  .block {
    margin-bottom: 4.5rem;
  }

  .block:last-of-type {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .scaffold {
    color: var(--ink);
    margin-bottom: 1.2rem;
  }

  .pull-quote {
    border-left: 2px solid var(--section-accent, var(--ink-dim));
    padding: 0.4rem 0 0.4rem 1.4rem;
    margin: 1.8rem 0;
  }

  .pull-quote p {
    font-size: clamp(1rem, 2.2vw, 1.25rem);
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--ink);
    margin-bottom: 0.6rem;
  }

  .pull-quote .translation {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    font-style: normal;
    color: var(--ink-dim);
  }

  .pull-quote cite {
    font-family: var(--font-ui);
    font-size: 0.7rem;
    font-style: normal;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--ink-dim);
  }
</style>
